Organizing my life lately has me going through all the photos I never got a chance to post, this one clearly during my short lived time with extensions. Anyway, here are my random thoughts on when people tell me, "It gets easier."

Since the day Nate was born, people were telling me, “It gets easier.” But when he was brand new, I didn’t find the transition nearly as hard as I thought it would be because I was on cloud 9. Then when the exhaustion slowly started overpowering the excitement, I found the lack of sleep got harder, not easier. Harder still was when Nate became mobile and my days of leaving him on his play mat while I ran to the bathroom were officially behind me. I guess it’s simpler now that he’s on a pretty set schedule and we’ve got a great routine going, but sometimes I question if it’s really easier. 

Long gone are the days I could feed Nate right from bed with a simple nursing session and forget about spending the day cuddling on the couch because as if he’ll sit still longer than one minute. I rarely find the time to finish my coffee these days because I’m non-stop running after little Nate who loves to climb on or under absolutely everything, including his stroller, even though he routinely gets his head stuck underneath. 

All to say, I’m not sure it gets easier. I’m more experienced for sure. Bath time isn’t scary anymore and Nate’s becoming more independent every day, but as he grows, so does the amount of energy it takes to keep him safe, well fed, and happy throughout the day. I love motherhood though. It’s the best thing I’ve ever done and even though it may not have gotten easier, it most definitely has gotten more fun.

Your thoughts? 📷 : @laurelcreative

{#NIAW} It wasn’t easy making peace with having to do IVF for male factor infertility and it was an especially hard balance figuring out how to be angry without making my husband feel guilty. Because infertility is no one’s fault. Going through it tested our relationship in so many ways, but every time it could have broken us, it made us stronger instead. 

I am so not ready to jump back into fertility treatments yet, but this time around, it’s less about the needles and more about the fear of it not working. I know I can face my needle phobia again, but I’m not sure I can handle a failed cycle. So that’s where we stand, in limbo, afraid to move forward, but also afraid not to as we are only getting older. 

I will say though that secondary infertility is nothing like I experienced with primary. Grief has been replaced by hope and desperation is now excitement at the prospect of giving little Nate a sibling. Just need to find the strength to try. 

And lastly, I learned the other week that the CDC changed the stat to 1 in 5, previously 1 in 8, couples that experience infertility in the US. Even if you don’t know anyone going through it, I promise… you do. 

Sending love and strength to all my fellow warriors. My inbox is always open.

I think the greatest realization I’ve had in my life this far is that you don’t change just because your surroundings do. I remember the day I decided to stay in Paris like it was yesterday. I was supposed to head back to America in a couple days, but as I sat with my friend at a cafe in Les Jardins des Tuileries, I looked around and couldn’t imagine leaving. I had no idea where I would live or what I would be getting myself into, but I never pass up an opportunity, so right then and there, I decided to just go for it. 

I learned a lot living in Paris… that bread belongs on the table (not your plate) and baguette dipped in coffee is surprisingly good, but more than that… I learned that you can move to an entirely new country all by yourself, but you will still be the same person, just in a new place. 

I studied the French language like it was my job, but I was still the same perfectionist, afraid to speak in case I made a grammatical error. And even though everyone wanted to talk to “The American,” the introvert in me still chose to keep my circle relatively small. 

I traded my smartphone for a French cell that didn’t work internationally, threw out my berets (only tourists wear them), and fully immersed myself in the culture. I had every opportunity to completely reinvent myself, but at the end of the day, while each experience changed and impacted me, we are who we are. Just something I think about from time to time.

Does it mean you’ve made it when you find a hate thread about yourself on Reddit? Asking for a friend. 🙃

I started Googling myself every once in a while ever since my stalker situation back in high school and as of yesterday’s search… apparently there are some people who really don’t like me. 

I know I know, I should just ignore it and focus on the multitude of incredibly kind messages I receive... but I’ve never been that kinda girl. So to the person who started the conversation saying they hate-watch me for hours, this one’s for you. ;)

I’m a terrible blogger. I say it all the time. I rarely post because I have a love/hate relationship with social media, but I garnered a large following because I started blogging over a decade ago (when I used to travel, event hop, and post much more frequently). And I’m sorry I’m boring, but I’m honestly a bit lost about where to take my page these days. I feel like I’ve covered every topic under the sun at this point and I try to be intentional with my posts because I know that even with terrible engagement (probably bc I barely post), I can see how many people my words are impacting. But what’s wrong with suggesting trivia night?? It’s so fun. I love going with friends, even though you don’t think I have any. But I don’t blame you there. As vulnerable as I get on here sometimes, I’m actually an incredibly private person who values connection over image, so I rarely touch my phone when I’m with other people.

Btw, you are SO right. I do make the same face in every photo. I’m not the biggest fan of being in front of the camera, so in order to get “the shot” quickly, I just go with what I know works.

And I LOVE being a husband woman. Never even heard that term before, but I’ll gladly accept the title. 👸 

Oh, and to the person who said my hair clips remind them of their grandma… lol

The end. Hope this was more entertaining for ya. I tried. Thanks for keeping my views up!

P.s. to the commenter who said they know me from high school and that I’m really nice… ily, whoever you are. 🫶🏻

Dw guys, I’m good. 😂

#respondingtohatecomments #nycblogger #nycmom #mommyblogger #toddlermom

Poolside. Pretty much the only way to get me in the water is to take me snorkeling. 

I’ve never particularly liked being underwater (in fact, I’m quite terrified of the ocean), but I forced myself to go snorkeling in Puerto Rico and now I’m addicted. It was just the most surreal experience watching the ocean light up and getting to swim with sea turtles was its own amazing adventure.

One of the best days of my life was actually snorkeling in the Blue Caves in Croatia. Aside from the fact that I got seasick on the tiny 8 seater boat we took there, the guide brought us to this little island afterward where only 14 people live (basically a family that runs a restaurant there overlooking the ocean). We got to eat red snapper that had literally just been caught and then swim in water so clear you could see your toes.

Do you prefer being in or out of the water?

When my husband and I became parents, we both agreed that we wanted to raise Nate with a strong sense of independence, so every day when Nate wakes up, I tell him, “You are capable.” And I am amazed as I watch him learn and grow and yes, sometimes struggle to accomplish our everyday tasks. 

Because I had no sense of what toddlers were capable of until I had one, here are some daily tasks Nate does as a 20 month old:
- Takes off his sleep sack (after I unzip)
- Turns off his sound machine
- Chooses what he wants for breakfast and then brings it to his high chair 
- Feeds himself (with some exceptions)
- Understands what constitutes garbage and throws things away accordingly 
- Puts the recycling in the bin (I separate it out)
- Finds and brings me his socks and shoes when it’s time to go out (although sometimes he pulls out socks from the laundry lol)
- Cleans up spills and puts his toys away (with help)
- Gets himself tissues and blows his nose as needed 
- Washes his hands with soap when we get home (I lift him up) 
- Puts his dirty clothes in the laundry basket 
- And now washes his own fruit thanks to this @lovevery sink :)

Feels like yesterday and a lifetime ago when he was born. 37 hours of labor, 4 hours of pushing, 3 IVs, over 20 bags of IV fluids, and an emergency c-section. And that’s after IVF. All I can say is this baby made me strong. 

Some of his favorite things at this age:
- Making more crumbs for me as I vacuum 
- Adding toys to my morning coffee 
- Waking me up 
- Borrowing my lipstick 
- Hiding my things in the recycling bin 
- BALLOONS 

No doubt he’ll make it through at least half the list today. ;) But in all seriousness, I could not be more obsessed with this child. The way he makes me hold both his hands as I rock him to sleep and how excited he gets just doing the laundry together. He is my bestest little friend and I couldn’t ask for a more adorable sidekick. 

Also… if only you could have seen his initial reaction. Omg. Happiest little boy. Can’t wait to see his face when he wakes up to cake after his nap. 

Who remembers when Nate was born??

My husband asks me all the time how I do it… spend all day with Nate giving him endless patience and love. Truth be told, one of my biggest fears going into motherhood was not knowing how I would find the patience for a child, but I’ve learned that by being present, it just comes naturally for me.

I’m not saying it’s always easy (or feasible), but when I’m with Nate, he is my sole focus. I view my time with him as if it were an office job in that in this moment, he is my only responsibility. By allowing myself to fully be present with him, the frustrations that normally come from trying to do everything at once no longer have the opportunity to form. That doesn’t mean I’m not multitasking every day when I’m trying to feed him breakfast and keep the apartment in order, but it does mean that the tasks I choose to do when I’m with him are also for him.

{Miscarriage after IVF} I was pregnant. Then I wasn’t. 

I was going to be a girl mom. Now I’m not.

Every month that passes I think about how far along I would have been, how close we were to becoming a family of 4. 

1 in 4 pregnancies end in miscarriage, but I am not 1 in 4. 

I’m in the 5% of IVF pregnancies that end, despite the fact that our embryo was tested,  genetically healthy, and highly graded. 

Everything I went through to get here, all the needles, the tens of thousands of dollars in doctor’s bills, the endless 7am appointments… it was all for nothing and we’ll never know why.

I rocked Nate to sleep the night we found out and told him I was sorry. I wanted so badly to give him a sibling. And then I fell into my husband’s arms, crying for our loss and for what this loss means.

We don’t get to try again. There’s only starting over. 

Another round of IVF. My personal hell that comes with a $40,000+ price tag. 

IVF isn’t a guarantee, but my body isn’t the issue, so I was naive thinking pregnancy loss would never be our story. But it’s my body that failed this time. And I’m not sure I’ll ever get over that.

There are certain moments in our lives that quite literally divide time into before and after. The day we got our male factor infertility diagnosis was one of them. That was the day everything we thought we knew changed. When the natural order of life became just a pipe dream. You fall in love, you get married, you have kids…

But that’s just not how it works for 1 in 5 couples in the US. 

We eventually embraced the fact that IVF would be our pathway to parenthood. I faced my needle phobia, we sacrificed our house fund to pay the exorbitant fees, and we went through the emotional turmoil that comes with this journey. And thank Gd, we were blessed with our little Nate. 

But to go through it again and walk away with nothing except bruises and bills… knowing that instead of welcoming our baby girl in just a matter of months, we need to start over, just for the chance to try again…

I’m not sure I could ever make you understand the pain. 

Miscarriage is devastating and cruel. Miscarriage after IVF… I have no words. 

I won’t lie, fertility issues are not easy on a marriage and pregnancy loss breaks you in ways you can’t imagine, but I do know the pain makes me a better mother.

It forces me to appreciate the mundane moments and never wish the time to move faster. It lets me savor every bedtime cuddle and recognize just how blessed I am to be Nate’s mama. And ours is the greatest love story I may ever have the privilege of knowing.
